<DOC><DOCNO> AP891122-0169 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1809EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-22 0379</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0391</SECOND><HEAD>West Is Fair But East Gets Snow And Rain</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Snow and rain, some of it heavy, fell across much of the easternhalf of the nation Wednesday, and more cold air swept across thecentral part of the nation.   Snow spread across much of the Ohio Valley during the afternoon,coming from the Great Lakes region and from a storm systemdeveloping over the Gulf Coast states.   A mixture of snow, sleet and freezing rain made traveltreacherous in southern Ohio, the National Weather Service said.   The storm system developing for the Gulf Coast states alsoproduced rain across much of the area from eastern Texas to thesouthern and central Appalachian Mountains.   Thunderstorms extended from southeastern Texas across centralLouisiana and central Mississippi.   The heaviest rain during the six-hour period up to 1 p.m. ESTwas 2.15 inches at Barksdale Air Force Base, near Shreveport, La.,while 1.19 inches fell at Monroe, La.   The storm over the central Gulf Coast was expected to tracktoward the northeast during the night, spreading Thanksgiving Daysnow across parts of the middle Atlantic Coast region.   Snow squalls were in parts of the upper Great Lakes during theafternoon, and 4 to 6 inches of snow was reported in the Milwaukeearea.   Light snow also fell across northern Illinois, with up to 2inches reported in the Chicago area. Light snow also extendedacross Iowa into eastern Nebraska and southeastern South Dakota.   Fair weather prevailed across the western half of the country,but dense fog developed from Tuesday into Wednesday in theCalifornia valleys and in northern Utah, snarling airport traffic.   Cold air spread across much of the central states, bringing anend to several days of unseasonably warm weather, as northwesterlywind gusting above 40 mph blew across the middle Mississippi Valleyand the central half of the Great Plains.   Afternoon temperatures were generally in the teens from UpperMichigan into the eastern Dakotas, with readings only in the singledigits in the Red River Valley on the border of Minnesota and NorthDakota.   In the Northeast, Binghamton, N.Y., had a record low of just 10degrees.   Wednesday's low for the Lower 48 states was 4 degrees below zeroat Grand Forks, N.D.</TEXT></DOC>